 ('352', '10', '3', '1', 'en_us', '44', '', '{\"typeId\":\"3\",\"authorId\":\"1\",\"title\":\"LivePerson Pricing Model Design\",\"slug\":\"liveperson-pricing-model\",\"postDate\":1430364600,\"expiryDate\":null,\"enabled\":1,\"fields\":{\"24\":\"<p>This is the analysis text.\\r\\n<\\/p><ul>\\r\\n\\t<li>The page doesn\'t impress me, as a first-time visitor after seeing a few slides in the header image area. It simply was not able to convey what it is.<\\/li>\\r\\n\\t<li>The look and feel of the overall layout didn\'t match its content. The logo could also be redesigned to be more coherent to a writer\'s community.<\\/li>\\r\\n\\t<li>There is no quick upload functionality for sharing your work and the sign up process is too long.<\\/li>\\r\\n\\t<li>Kanjy allows writers to create portfolios of their work, but it\'s still not sufficient to make the whole community an active network.<\\/li>\\r\\n<\\/ul>\",\"39\":\"\",\"23\":\"Analysis Heading\",\"20\":\"<p>I led the website UX design for LivePerson global where I worked. The goal I set is to reshape the brand\\u2019s online presence, through creating a sleek user interface and transferring the site focus to B2C which would offer more engaging online experiences for customers.<\\/p><p>As a IA and UX person, I conducted researches and came up with a series of ideations before planning and restructuring the site, followed by some important considerations from both design and development point of view.<\\/p>\",\"19\":\"Project Brief\",\"10\":\"LivePerson\",\"11\":\"http:\\/\\/www.liveperson.com\\/\",\"58\":\"yellow\",\"25\":{\"219\":{\"type\":\"mediaFeature\",\"enabled\":\"1\",\"fields\":{\"heading\":\"Original Pricing Model & Painpoint\",\"body\":\"<p>After changing from the old plan, the same issues are still relevant with the new pricing model and sale strategy:\\r\\n<\\/p><ul>\\r\\n\\t<li>Visitors want to see pricings and features in the same table<\\/li>\\r\\n\\t<li>Visitors want to understand the differences between plans and goals<\\/li>\\r\\n\\t<li>Visitors do not understand the buzz words (which do not sound like buzz words)<\\/li><\\/ul>\",\"media\":[\"218\"],\"layout\":\"fluid\",\"device\":\"none\",\"allowEnlarge\":\"\"}},\"146\":{\"type\":\"mediaFeature\",\"enabled\":\"\",\"fields\":{\"heading\":\"Design - Wireframes\",\"body\":\"<p>Based on the above data and user analysis, I think the key point for the new pricing page should be:\\r\\n<\\/p><ul>\\r\\n\\t<li>Focus on Pricing itself instead of explain un unfamiliar concept for visitors(especially as we are using a new pricing model and drive traffic, there will be more first-time-visitor.)<\\/li>\\r\\n\\t<li>Clearly present what we sell to visitors: it is a combo of partially functional mobile app and a web dashboard, so what users finally get will meet their expectation.<\\/li>\\r\\n\\t<li>\\\"Why should I pay if you have a free plan?\\\" will be the No1 question visitor will ask if he\\/ she see our pricing page; emphasize the free plan but also compare it with our other plan.<\\/li>\\r\\n\\t<li>Target visitors better by supplying related testimonial and Q&As (also valuable for future analysis and improvement.)<\\/li>\\r\\n<\\/ul>\",\"media\":[\"144\",\"145\"],\"layout\":\"full\",\"device\":\"none\",\"allowEnlarge\":\"\"}},\"149\":{\"type\":\"comparisonFeature\",\"enabled\":\"1\",\"fields\":{\"heading\":\"Design - Wireframes\",\"body\":\"<p>Based on the above data and user analysis, I think the key point for the new pricing page should be:<\\/p><ul><li>Focus on Pricing itself instead of explain un unfamiliar concept for visitors(especially as we are using a new pricing model and drive traffic, there will be more first-time-visitor.)<\\/li><li>Clearly present what we sell to visitors: it is a combo of partially functional mobile app and a web dashboard, so what users finally get will meet their expectation.<\\/li><li>\\\"Why should I pay if you have a free plan?\\\" will be the No1 question visitor will ask if he\\/ she see our pricing page; emphasize the free plan but also compare it with our other plan.<\\/li><li>Target visitors better by supplying related testimonial and Q&As (also valuable for future analysis and improvement.)<\\/li><\\/ul>\",\"images\":[\"147\",\"148\"],\"firstCaption\":\"Plan A\",\"secondCaption\":\"Plan B\",\"fadeEnabled\":\"1\"}},\"19\":{\"type\":\"mediaFeature\",\"enabled\":\"1\",\"fields\":{\"heading\":\"Other works at\\r\\nLivePerson\",\"body\":\"<p>Details are available upon request.<\\/p>\",\"media\":[\"141\",\"142\"],\"layout\":\"fluid\",\"device\":\"none\",\"allowEnlarge\":\"\"}},\"65\":{\"type\":\"responsiveFeature\",\"enabled\":\"1\",\"fields\":{\"heading\":\"Responsive Design\",\"body\":\"<p>This is the text content for responsive design feature. This is the text content for responsive design feature. This is the text content for responsive design feature. This is the text content for responsive design feature.<\\/p>\",\"desktopScreen\":[\"67\"],\"tabletScreen\":[\"66\"],\"mobileScreen\":[\"64\"],\"allowEnlarge\":\"1\"}}},\"49\":\"Web Design\",\"14\":\"LivePerson\\r\\nPricing Model\\r\\nDesign\",\"22\":\"<p>I\'ve learned a lot.<\\/p>\",\"21\":\"What I\'ve Learned\",\"43\":[\"133\"],\"17\":\"\",\"18\":\"\",\"16\":\"\",\"13\":[\"7\"],\"42\":[\"111\"],\"50\":\"\",\"44\":[\"95\"],\"12\":\"Visual Design\",\"3\":\"I led the UX design for LivePerson where I worked. My goal is to reshape the brand\\u2019s online presence by creating a sleek user interface and transferring the focus to B2C.\",\"9\":[\"photoshop\"],\"4\":\"2014\"}}', '2015-08-29 21:43:01', '2015-08-29 21:43:01', 'e7547597-0a19-4155-971a-659144acbb6d'),
 ('353', '184', '3', '1', 'en_us', '16', '', '{\"typeId\":\"3\",\"authorId\":\"1\",\"title\":\"ACCPI Community Website\",\"slug\":\"accpi\",\"postDate\":1440474060,\"expiryDate\":null,\"enabled\":1,\"fields\":{\"24\":\"<p>When we\\u2019re thinking about acquiring users, it\\u2019s easy to assume that \\\"friction\\\" is the enemy of traction. That\\u2019s why many products make signing up so simple \\u2014 the fewer fields, the better. But that only really works when your user\\u2019s satisfaction doesn\\u2019t depend on other users. In the case of a web platform, such as a social network or marketplace, the quality of users and their interactions define a good product and experience. In fact, to achieve scale in a platform model, good UX design often requires that you filter out bad users.\\r\\n<\\/p><p>Think about Product Hunt. If anyone could post a product, spammers would turn the experience into a 24\\/7 infomercial. By requiring a nomination from \\u201cthe most engaged and thoughtful contributors\\u201d in the community, they\\u2019re carefully curating the content by first curating the people who can post.\\r\\n<\\/p><p>Even in products that don\\u2019t focus on community-generated content, user quality still matters. Think about a dating website like Match.com or caregiving site Care.com. For these sites, the users <em>are<\\/em> the product. So some level of friction in the sign-up process will help deter or actively block bad eggs. But it is also true that visitors cannot fill everything out at the first stage, so it is also important to create a progress profile completion system like Linkedin.\\r\\n<\\/p><p>So what motivated customer care professionals to join our community? Besides the attractive game campaigns, the material reward, maybe we should think inside out, about how our community can encourage them to learn, share and resonate with other people with same interests and experiences.\\r\\n<\\/p><p>The key concept to understand is that <strong>motivation<\\/strong> is difficult to change. Don\'t focus on it. Rewards are great but not effective <strong>unless they perform the behavior first.<\\/strong>\\r\\n<\\/p>\",\"39\":\"\",\"23\":\"Reaserch & Analysis\",\"20\":\"<p>My design goal is to gather a thriving global profession of best-in-class customer cares experts across all industries, and LP also influences the community by sharing knowledge and provides trainings as industry lead; Builds up a member-driven organization committed to promoting customer care and customer engagement as a competitive advantage in business; This website can be a soft sale tool that Introduce LP\'s 2.0 platform, mobile applications and its benefits.<\\/p><p>I led the website UX design for ACCPI commnity site. The goal is to reshape the LivePerson\'s (LP) brand\\u2019s online presence, through creating a sleek sharable community experiences and transferring the site focus to nurturing a customer care professional which would offer more engaging online experiences for customers. As a IA and UX person, I conducted researches and came up with a series of ideations before planning and restructuring the site, followed by important considerations from both design and development point of view. Here is a work in progress for ACCPI website.\\r\\n<\\/p><ul>\\r\\n\\t<li>Research & analysis<\\/li>\\r\\n\\t<li>IA & sitemap<\\/li>\\r\\n\\t<li>Persona<\\/li>\\r\\n\\t<li>Use flow<\\/li>\\r\\n\\t<li>Wireframes<\\/li>\\r\\n\\t<li>Interactive prototype<\\/li>\\r\\n\\t<li>Testing<\\/li>\\r\\n<\\/ul>\",\"19\":\"Project Brief\",\"10\":\"LivePerson\",\"11\":\"http:\\/\\/www.liveperson.com\\/\",\"58\":\"yellow\",\"25\":{\"185\":{\"type\":\"mediaFeature\",\"enabled\":\"1\",\"fields\":{\"heading\":\"Persona\",\"body\":\"<p>In order to demostrate our target audience for ACCPI, I\'ve created 5 personas, here list two as examples. Their working experience level as a customer care professional is about junior to mid-weight. Full persona list and analysis wi