 ('475', '6', '3', '1', 'en_us', '99', '', '{\"typeId\":\"3\",\"authorId\":\"1\",\"title\":\"Real-Time Fengshui\",\"slug\":\"real-time-fengshui\",\"postDate\":1430281020,\"expiryDate\":null,\"enabled\":1,\"fields\":{\"24\":\"<p>Feng shui, as a theory that is a bit obscure, makes most of its regarding websites less interesting in design. During the existing products research I\'ve conducted, the common problems is: the related cultural symbols and patterns tend to be abused, and with a page full of incomprehensible theories, it appears to be pseudoscience. Ultimately, they all contribute to an obscure reading experience that one can feel difficult to learn from. Actually, the common design pattern is using some relevant images (or even irrelevant ones) surrounding textural information. The common design issues are:<br><\\/p><ul><li>Heavy copy, irrelevant links.<\\/li><li>Long pages of overwhelming information.<\\/li><li>Most Feng shui introduce this theory in an imperative tone.<\\/li><\\/ul><p><br><\\/p><p>In Contrary, with my project, Real-time Fengshui, I\'d like to introduce this theory through storytelling and teach its principals through real-time problem solving, as well as give the user down-to-earth tips.<\\/p><p>I also curious about what is the best learning curve\\/format for users? What is the ideally opening story for those site visitors without background information about fengshui at all? What makes users excited about the fengshui and what benefit them the most? I come up a questionaire with 9 questions and asked 19 target audience* to fill the survey. To my surprise, most respondents would like to jump into practical and visualized case study which can be applied to daily life. <\\/p><ul><li>88.9% of respondents are looking for basic and simple feng shui advices.<\\/li><li>Their main interests in feng shui relate to how this concept can be used in real life.<\\/li><li>Users are expecting a visualized interactive learning process.<\\/li><\\/ul><p><br>